      "title": "Crystal Clear",
      "text": "In 1953, while working a hotel switchboard, a college graduate named [[Shea Zellweger]] began a journey of wonder and obsession that would eventually lead to the invention of a radically new notation for logic. From a basement in Ohio, guided literally by his dreams and his innate love of [[pattern]], Zellweger developed an extraordinary visual system—called [[the “Logic Alphabet”]]—in which a group of specially designed letter-shapes can be manipulated like puzzles to reveal the geometric [[patterns]] underpinning logic."
